Exploratory Data Analysis: Titanic Survivorship Data

Research Question

Motivating question: Did economic status determine survival for Titanic passengers?

What variable is the best proxy of socio-economic status?

What other potential explanatory variables can we see in the data?

  • Are any of them likely to be confounding with economic status?
titanic  <- read.csv("https://web.stanford.edu/class/archive/cs/cs109/cs109.1166/stuff/titanic.csv")

Data Cleaning (Skipped)

Univariate Analysis

  • Significantly more male passengers than females
  • Positive outliers in passenger fare
# Is the amount you paid a good indicator of economic status?
titanic %>% pivot_longer(cols=all_of(c("Age", "Fare")), names_to="cat", values_to="value") %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = value)) +
  facet_wrap(~ cat, nrow = 2)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# There are some outlier fares
# Check the distributions for other potential explanatory variables for survival

titanic %>% select(Survived, Pclass, Sex, Siblings.Spouses.Aboard, Parents.Children.Aboard) %>%
  mutate(Siblings.Spouses.Aboard = ifelse(Siblings.Spouses.Aboard > 0, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(Parents.Children.Aboard = ifelse(Parents.Children.Aboard > 0, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather("cat", "value") %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = value), stat='count') +
  facet_wrap(~ cat, nrow = 2, scale="free")
## Warning in geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = value), stat = "count"): Ignoring
## unknown parameters: `binwidth`, `bins`, and `pad`

### Multivariate Analysis

# is there a relationship between age and fare?
titanic %>% select(Fare, Age) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Age, y = Fare)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Defining economic class: Fare or Passenger Class?

  • Outliers for fares in passenger classes 2 and 3 might reach into the next highest class, but it appears the bulk of the distribution for each class stay in the expected order.
# Does passenger class determine fare?

titanic %>% select(Fare, Pclass) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = Pclass, y = Fare, group = Pclass))

titanic %>% group_by(Pclass) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  print()
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   Pclass count
##    <int> <int>
## 1      1   216
## 2      2   184
## 3      3   487

Which variables seem to correlate with survival?

  • Sex and presence of family seem correlated with survival, but females were much more likely to be traveling with family.

  • Age does not seem to be correlated with fare, nor do survivors and non-survivors have very different age distributions.

titanic %>% mutate(Survived = as.factor(Survived)) %>%
  select(Survived, Sex) %>%
  group_by(Sex, Survived) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(fill=Survived, y=count, x=Sex)) +
  geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Sex'. You can override using the `.groups`
## argument.

titanic %>% mutate(Survived = as.factor(Survived)) %>%
  mutate(Family.Aboard = ifelse(Siblings.Spouses.Aboard + Parents.Children.Aboard > 0, "Yes", "No")) %>%
  select(Survived, Family.Aboard) %>%
  group_by(Family.Aboard, Survived) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(fill=Survived, y=count, x=Family.Aboard)) +
  geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Family.Aboard'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

titanic %>% select(Survived, Age) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = Survived, y = Age, group = Survived))

titanic %>% mutate(Family.Aboard = ifelse(Siblings.Spouses.Aboard + Parents.Children.Aboard > 0, "Yes", "No")) %>%
  select(Sex, Family.Aboard) %>%
  group_by(Sex, Family.Aboard) %>%
  summarise(count=n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(fill=Sex, y=count, x=Family.Aboard)) +
  geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity")
